 =20

The way a bank works is that it borrows short to lend long. Simplistically,=
 a bank might get its money from demand deposits, checking=C2=A0and savings=
 accounts that customers can withdraw at any time. And the bank might=C2=A0=
pay, say, 0% interest on those deposits. And then it invests the money in s=
ome longer-term assets, loans and bonds that don=E2=80=99t get paid back fo=
r years, and that pay, say, 2% interest. The bank earns 2% on its money, pa=
ys 0% to depositors for the money, and keeps the spread, the net interest m=
argin,=C2=A0which is 2% in this example.
Sometimes interest rates go up or down, though. Simplistically, short-term =
interest rates in the US are set by the Federal Reserve, which will raise i=
nterest rates to cool the economy if inflation is too high.
This is a risk for a bank=E2=80=99s borrow-short-to-lend-long business mode=
l. If the Fed suddenly raises short-term interest rates to, say, 3%, then y=
ou have to start paying 3% on your deposits. Meanwhile long-term interest r=
ates have probably also gone up to, say, 5%, but you are still earning the =
old 2% on your loans and bonds, because they are long-term loans that don=
=E2=80=99t get paid back for years. Your net interest margin is now negativ=
e 1%: You pay 3% on deposits and earn only 2% on loans and bonds.
This is an obvious problem and much of the business of banking is about man=
aging it. Here are some simple things that you can do:
=09Your loans and bonds have laddered maturities: Some mature next week, so=
me in 3 years, some in 6. So as rates go up, your loans and bonds are const=
antly rolling off and you are reinvesting the money in new loans and bonds =
at higher rates.=09When the Fed raises rates, in actual fact, banks mostly=
=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0pass along the whole rate increase to depositors. =
It=E2=80=99s a pain to switch banks, and most depositors don=E2=80=99t pay =
that much attention to rates. The =E2=80=9Cdeposit beta=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the sensitivity of bank deposit rate increases=C2=A0to Fed interest r=
ate increases =E2=80=94=C2=A0is lower than 1. So if the Fed raises rates fr=
om 0% to 3%, you might end up paying only, say, 0.5% on deposits.
  [1]

=09You can try to match your assets and liabilities somewhat. Make some sho=
rt-term loans, and some floating-rate loans, so that your assets are more s=
ensitive to rising rates. Borrow some money with long-term bonds, so that y=
our liabilities are less sensitive to rising rates. Do interest-rate swaps =
to hedge.=09You can make money in ways other than net interest margin: Char=
ge overdraft fees or do investment banking or trade securities or whatever.

This is not, however, the biggest problem with borrowing short to lend long=
. The biggest problem is that your depositors might all ask for their money=
 back tomorrow, and you might not be able to get the money back from your b=
orrowers for years. This problem is known as a =E2=80=9Cbank run=E2=80=9D a=
nd is famous from, you know, the  Diamond-Dybvig model that  won a Nobel Pr=
ize last year, or from It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life. =E2=80=9CThe money=E2=
=80=99s not here. Why, your money=E2=80=99s in Joe=E2=80=99s house,=E2=80=
=9D etc.=C2=A0
Much of the business of banking, and of bank=C2=A0regulation, is about mana=
ging=C2=A0this=C2=A0risk. For instance:
=09The government can provide deposit insurance on accounts, promising depo=
sitors that they=E2=80=99ll get their money back, which will make them less=
=C2=A0inclined to ask for their money back, since they know it=E2=80=99s sa=
fe.=C2=A0=09The government can regulate banks to make them act safely, so t=
hat they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0lose customer money, so that customers are conf=
ident and don=E2=80=99t ask for their money back.=09You can keep a lot of c=
ash around, so that if a lot of depositors (though certainly not all of the=
m) ask for their money back, you have some to give to them.=09If a lot of d=
epositors ask for their money back and you run through your cash, you can=
=C2=A0sell=C2=A0some of your loans or bonds to raise money. In the days of=
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life=C2=A0it was kind of hard to sell the mo=
rtgage on Joe=E2=80=99s house for ready cash, but modern financial markets =
are much deeper and more liquid, which is good for selling bonds or loans o=
r other bank assets.=C2=A0=09Alternatively, you can=C2=A0borrow against=C2=
=A0your assets: You can go to a bigger bank, or to a lender of last resort=
=C2=A0like the Federal Reserve,=C2=A0 or a =E2=80=9C  lender of next-to-las=
t resort=E2=80=9D like the Federal Home Loan Banks, and=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0th=
e cash to pay out depositors. And as collateral for that loan to you, you p=
ost your assets, the bonds you own or the loans you made to your customers.=
 This is the most classic way to deal with bank runs, and is famous from Wa=
lter Bagehot=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Lombard Street.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CLend freely, at a=
 penalty rate, against=C2=A0good collateral=E2=80=9D is  the basic advice=
=C2=A0Bagehot gives=C2=A0central bankers: If a bank has good loans, but it =
can=E2=80=99t turn them into money right away, the central bank should lend=
 it the money.

Let=E2=80=99s talk about Option 4,=C2=A0selling=C2=A0assets to raise money =
to pay back depositors. Let=E2=80=99s say you loaned a customer $100 for fi=
ve years at 2% interest. The customer is big and reliable and the loan will=
 definitely be paid back.=C2=A0How much can you sell that loan for? Well, t=
he day after you made the loan, it should be worth about $100 =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0about what you paid for it. But what if the Fed raises short-term intere=
st rates from 0% to 3%? Then the market interest rate on loans like this wi=
ll probably go up from 2% to 5%. But your loan still pays only 2%, so it is=
 worth less. The crude intuitive math is that a new market-rate loan would =
pay $5 of interest per year for 5 years ($25 total), while your loan pays $=
2 of interest for 5 years ($10 total), so it is worth about $15 less, so pe=
ople would pay you about $85 for it, though you=E2=80=99d get fired at a ba=
nk for doing bond math like that.=C2=A0(Really they=E2=80=99d pay you about=
 $87.
  [2]
)
There is a connection here=C2=A0to the previous problem, the one about your=
 net interest income going down as rates go up. Imagine a super-simple bank=
: You=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0$100 at 0% and lend=C2=A0$100 at 2% for five years. =
You also invest $10 of your own capital in the bank, and keep that money in=
 cash, to cover any sudden withdrawals.
  [3]
=C2=A0You make $2 per year in interest, pay=C2=A0$0 per year of interest, a=
nd get=C2=A0$2 per year of net interest margin. You spend $1.50 of that on =
non-interest expense (salaries, rent, etc.),=C2=A0and keep $0.50 as profit.=
 After a year, you have $10.50 of capital: the $10 you put in and your $0.5=
0 of profit.=C2=A0
Then rates suddenly go up, so short-term rates are now 3% and long-term rat=
es are 5%.=C2=A0None of the stuff I said before =E2=80=94=C2=A0about deposi=
t betas and laddered maturities =E2=80=94=C2=A0works for you, for whatever =
reason; your deposit rates immediately jump to 3% and you keep getting 2% o=
n your bonds. This year, you will have a net loss of $2.50: You pay $3 on y=
our $100 of deposits and get=C2=A0paid $2 on your $100 of bonds, and you al=
so have $1.50 of salaries and rent to pay. (You=E2=80=99ll be down to $8 of=
 your own capital.) Next year, you will also have a net loss, though maybe =
it=E2=80=99s only $2 because you laid some people off and closed some branc=
hes.=C2=A0(Now you=E2=80=99re down to $6 of capital.) Year after, same idea=
: You will keep bleeding money, because you borrowed short and loaned long =
and rates went up. But maybe something will change? Maybe rates will go bac=
k down. Maybe your borrowers will repay their bonds early and you=E2=80=99l=
l get to redeploy the money at higher rates. Maybe your employees will find=
 a new line of business to earn some fees. Maybe you=E2=80=99ll reverse the=
 losses. Or not, maybe you=E2=80=99ll keep losing $2.50 per year for five y=
ears and run out of capital and have to close the bank.=C2=A0But maybe my a=
ssumptions about your high deposit beta and long-term assets are unrealisti=
cally pessimistic: This is a simplistic example, and at a real bank the res=
ult might be lower margins for a while, not constant losses.
But what if instead of keeping their deposits at your bank and earning 3% i=
nterest, the depositors all asked for their money back today? You would hav=
e to sell your bonds. You=E2=80=99d get about $87 for them. You would have =
a $13 loss=C2=A0today. All of the losses that you=C2=A0would=C2=A0have take=
n over the next five years, from holding long-term bonds at low rates while=
 deposit rates have gone up, you will experience=C2=A0now. And you won=E2=
=80=99t have any time to reverse them, because you have to sell the bonds n=
ow and give everyone their money back. Also you don=E2=80=99t have enough m=
oney: Selling the bonds for $87 will raise $87, and you have $10 of capital=
, for a total of $97. But your depositors want their $100 back, and you onl=
y have $97.
If you are a bank that borrowed short to lend long, and rates go up, your p=
ortfolio of long-dated assets represents an=C2=A0opportunity cost over time=
:=C2=A0Instead of earning 5% on your loans, you=E2=80=99re stuck earning 2%=
. But if you have to sell those assets, you turn that opportunity cost into=
 a cash loss today. You pull the losses forward in time and take them all n=
ow.
Now we have to talk about accounting. Oversimplifying, there are two main w=
ays for a bank to account for its assets:
=09The traditional way is to account for them at cost, the price you paid f=
or them. If you lend a customer $100, you have a $100 asset =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0on your balance sheet. (You deduct something for th=
e possibility they won=E2=80=99t pay you back,=C2=A0but let=E2=80=99s ignor=
e that.)=09The other way is to account for them at their fair market value.=
 If you buy a bond for $100, you can go look at the market price for that b=
ond at the end of the quarter; if it=E2=80=99s $97.75, then you have a $97.=
75 asset on your balance sheet. The other $2.25 is gone.
  [4]



The first approach gives you a reasonable picture of a bank that is continu=
ing to operate as a bank: In my example, if you have $100 of bonds and $100=
 of deposits and the loans pay 2% and the deposits cost 3% and you are losi=
ng $2.50 per year, your financial statements=C2=A0will=C2=A0say that. Your =
balance sheet=C2=A0will say that you have $100 of bonds, so you will ultima=
tely have enough money to pay back your depositors, but your income stateme=
nt will say you are losing money each year.
The second approach gives you a reasonably accurate picture of a bank that =
has to shut down today: In my example, your balance sheet will show that yo=
u have=C2=A0$87 of bonds at fair market value, so you don=E2=80=99t have en=
ough money to pay back all your depositors if you have to do it today.
Traditionally banks=E2=80=99 assets consisted mostly of=C2=A0loans, there w=
as not much of a market for those loans, and the normal accounting approach=
 was to account for them at cost. Modern banks=E2=80=99 assets include lots=
 of=C2=A0bonds, there is a market for those bonds, and it is reasonably com=
mon to account for them at fair market value.
  [5]
=C2=A0Still, banks do=C2=A0like accounting for assets at cost, and so they =
are allowed to=C2=A0designate bonds as =E2=80=9Cheld to maturity=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning that they have no plans to sell them =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and account for them at cost. (But then if they sell any of their held-to-m=
aturity bonds, they  need to reclassify=C2=A0all=C2=A0of them as =E2=80=9Ca=
vailable for sale=E2=80=9D and account for them at fair market value, which=
 could mean taking a huge loss all at once.) In general it seems fair to sa=
y that the modern trend in financial-institution accounting is toward marki=
ng more things to market values, but there remain many exceptions.
  [6]

From my simple example you can see why banks don=E2=80=99t always like mark=
-to-market accounting. In my simple example, the bank has $100 of deposits,=
 $100 of bonds and $10 of capital. It is losing money on interest rates, so=
 its capital is going down, slowly. But it is solvent: It has assets of $11=
0 ($100 of bonds plus $10 of cash) and liabilities of only $100 (the deposi=
ts).=C2=A0
But if the bank instead put out financial statements showing that it had $8=
7 of bonds (their current market value), it would be insolvent: It would ha=
ve assets of $97 against liabilities of $100. And if its depositors read th=
ose financial statements, they=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Chey wait this bank is=
 insolvent=E2=80=9D and rush to take their money out. And then the bank=C2=
=A0would have to sell those bonds for $87, and it really=C2=A0would=C2=A0be=
 insolvent. The accounting could cause a run, which would require the asset=
s to be sold at market value, which would result in taking all the losses t=
oday, which would result in actual insolvency.
One crude way that the actual US banking system deals with this problem is =
by letting banks account for their held-to-maturity bonds at cost on their =
balance sheet, but then making them explain, somewhere in the footnotes to =
the financial statements, their current market value.
  [7]
 This feels like in some ways a fair compromise. On the other hand someone =
might read the footnotes! I mean, not most people. But someone might, and t=
hey might explain the footnotes in a readable way =E2=80=94=C2=A0they might=
  say something like =E2=80=9Con a mark-to-market basis, they were broke la=
st quarter=E2=80=9D
  [8]
 =E2=80=94 and people might read that and think =E2=80=9Chuh that=E2=80=99s=
 bad=E2=80=9D and withdraw their deposits. Causing the bonds to be sold, ca=
using insolvency.
But wait! Why=C2=A0sell=C2=A0the bonds? Why not=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0against th=
em? You have $100 of bonds, $10 of capital kept in cash, $100 of deposits. =
Rates move against you. In a footnote to your financial statements, you con=
fess that the bonds are worth only $87 at current market values. Someone re=
ads the footnote and shows it to someone else. Word gets around. Lots of de=
positors come and ask for their money back. You have only $10 of cash.=C2=
=A0
So you go to your lender of last resort, let=E2=80=99s say the Federal Rese=
rve. You say: =E2=80=9CHere is a $100 asset that I have. I want to post it =
as collateral for a loan. You lend me $100 against this collateral, and cha=
rge me 3% interest. I will use the $100 to pay off my depositors. I=E2=80=
=99ll be left with a $100 asset and a $100 liability to you, instead of to =
my depositors. And then I=E2=80=99ll try to cut costs and earn more fees an=
d otherwise earn enough to pay your interest. I=E2=80=99ll be in the same p=
lace as I was before the run. It=E2=80=99s not a=C2=A0great=C2=A0place, nec=
essarily =E2=80=94=C2=A0I=E2=80=99m still earning less interest on my asset=
s than I=E2=80=99m paying on my liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, you know, m=
arkets change and I=E2=80=99ll probably muddle through and anyway the bonds=
 will eventually pay off $100 so you=E2=80=99ll get your money back.=E2=80=
=9D
And then the Fed either says:
=09sure, or=09=E2=80=9Cno, this is not $100 of collateral, this is only $87=
 of collateral: We will only lend against the=C2=A0market value=C2=A0of thi=
s collateral, not against=C2=A0what you paid for it.=E2=80=9D

Which answer should the Fed give? On the one hand, the Fed wants to lend ag=
ainst good collateral and not take a lot of risk. Lending you $100 against =
collateral with a market value of $87 seems kind of stupid for the Fed.
On the other hand, the Fed is a lender of last resort, and its main job is =
to lend you money so that you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have to sell your ass=
ets too hastily. Lending against the market value is kind of the same thing=
