<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way a bank works is that it borrows short =
to lend long. Simplistically, a bank might get its money from demand deposi=
ts, checking=C2=A0and savings accounts that customers can withdraw at any t=
ime. And the bank might=C2=A0pay, say, 0% interest on those deposits. And t=
hen it invests the money in some longer-term assets, loans and bonds that d=
on=E2=80=99t get paid back for years, and that pay, say, 2% interest. The b=
ank earns 2% on its money, pays 0% to depositors for the money, and keeps t=
he spread, the net interest margin,=C2=A0which is 2% in this example.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes interest rates go up or down, though=
. Simplistically, short-term interest rates in the US are set by the Federa=
l Reserve, which will raise interest rates to cool the economy if inflation=
 is too high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a risk for a bank=E2=80=99s borrow-sho=
rt-to-lend-long business model. If the Fed suddenly raises short-term inter=
est rates to, say, 3%, then you have to start paying 3% on your deposits. M=
eanwhile long-term interest rates have probably also gone up to, say, 5%, b=
ut you are still earning the old 2% on your loans and bonds, because they a=
re long-term loans that don=E2=80=99t get paid back for years. Your net int=
erest margin is now negative 1%: You pay 3% on deposits and earn only 2% on=
 loans and bonds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is an obvious problem and much of the bus=
iness of banking is about managing it. Here are some simple things that you=
 can do:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your loans and bonds have laddered ma=
turities: Some mature next week, some in 3 years, some in 6. So as rates go=
 up, your loans and bonds are constantly rolling off and you are reinvestin=
g the money in new loans and bonds at higher rates.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">When the Fed raises rates, in actual fact, banks mostly=
=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>pass along the whole rate increase to dep=
ositors. It=E2=80=99s a pain to switch banks, and most depositors don=E2=80=
=99t pay that much attention to rates. The =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30821211.285418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjMvd2h5LWlzLXRoZS1pbnRlcmVzdC1yYXRl=
LW9uLW15LXNhdmluZ3MtYWNjb3VudC1zby1sb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzEzJn=
