und-color: #ccc;">The money=E2=80=99s not here</a>. Why, your money=E2=80=
=99s in Joe=E2=80=99s house,=E2=80=9D etc.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of the business of banking, and of bank=
=C2=A0regulation, is about managing=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>risk. For insta=
nce:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The government can provide deposit in=
surance on accounts, promising depositors that they=E2=80=99ll get their mo=
ney back, which will make them less=C2=A0<em>inclined </em>to ask for their=
 money back, since they know it=E2=80=99s safe.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">The government can regulate banks to make them act safe=
ly, so that they don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0lose customer money, so that customers =
are confident and don=E2=80=99t ask for their money back.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can keep a lot of cash around, so that if a lo=
t of depositors (though certainly not all of them) ask for their money back=
, you have some to give to them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I=
f a lot of depositors ask for their money back and you run through your cas=
h, you can=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>some of your loans or bonds to raise mon=
ey. In the days of=C2=A0<em>It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life=C2=A0</em>it was =
kind of hard to sell the mortgage on Joe=E2=80=99s house for ready cash, bu=
t modern financial markets are much deeper and more liquid, which is good f=
or selling bonds or loans or other bank assets.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Alternatively, you can=C2=A0<em>borrow against=C2=A0</e=
m>your assets: You can go to a bigger bank, or to a lender of last resort=
=C2=A0like the Federal Reserve,=C2=A0 or a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30821211.285418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvZmVkZXJhbC1ob21lLWxvYW4tYmFua3Mt=
dG8tcmFpc2UtNjQtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1ub3Rlcy1vZmZlcmluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzEzMjNfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yMzAzMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd62ff072=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">  lender of next-to-last resort</a>=E2=80=9D like the Federal Hom=
e Loan Banks, and=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0the cash to pay out depositors. And as c=
ollateral for that loan to you, you post your assets, the bonds you own or =
the loans you made to your customers. This is the most classic way to deal =
with bank runs, and is famous from Walter Bagehot=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>Lombar=
d Street.=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=9CLend freely, at a penalty rate, against=C2=A0g=
ood collateral=E2=80=9D is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/30821211.285418/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTG9tYmFyZF=
