blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> the basic advice</a>=C2=A0Bagehot gives=C2=A0cent=
ral bankers: If a bank has good loans, but it can=E2=80=99t turn them into =
money right away, the central bank should lend it the money.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s talk about Option 4,=C2=A0<em>se=
lling=C2=A0</em>assets to raise money to pay back depositors. Let=E2=80=99s=
 say you loaned a customer $100 for five years at 2% interest. The customer=
 is big and reliable and the loan will definitely be paid back.=C2=A0How mu=
ch can you sell that loan for? Well, the day after you made the loan, it sh=
ould be worth about $100 =E2=80=94=C2=A0about what you paid for it. But wha=
t if the Fed raises short-term interest rates from 0% to 3%? Then the marke=
t interest rate on loans like this will probably go up from 2% to 5%. But y=
our loan still pays only 2%, so it is worth less. The crude intuitive math =
is that a new market-rate loan would pay $5 of interest per year for 5 year=
s ($25 total), while your loan pays $2 of interest for 5 years ($10 total),=
 so it is worth about $15 less, so people would pay you about $85 for it, t=
hough you=E2=80=99d get fired at a bank for doing bond math like that.=C2=
=A0(Really they=E2=80=99d pay you about $87.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a connection here=C2=A0to the previou=
s problem, the one about your net interest income going down as rates go up=
. Imagine a super-simple bank: You=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0$100 at 0% and lend=C2=
=A0$100 at 2% for five years. You also invest $10 of your own capital in th=
e bank, and keep that money in cash, to cover any sudden withdrawals.<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent=
 !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You make $2 per year in interest, pay=C2=A0$0 per year of interes=
t, and get=C2=A0$2 per year of net interest margin. You spend $1.50 of that=
 on non-interest expense (salaries, rent, etc.),=C2=A0and keep $0.50 as pro=
fit. After a year, you have $10.50 of capital: the $10 you put in and your =
$0.50 of profit.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then rates suddenly go up, so short-term rates=
 are now 3% and long-term rates are 5%.=C2=A0None of the stuff I said befor=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0about deposit betas and laddered maturities =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0works for you, for whatever reason; your deposit rates immediately jump =
to 3% and you keep getting 2% on your bonds. This year, you will have a net=
 loss of $2.50: You pay $3 on your $100 of deposits and get=C2=A0paid $2 on=
 your $100 of bonds, and you also have $1.50 of salaries and rent to pay. (=
You=E2=80=99ll be down to $8 of your own capital.) Next year, you will also=
 have a net loss, though maybe it=E2=80=99s only $2 because you laid some p=
eople off and closed some branches.=C2=A0(Now you=E2=80=99re down to $6 of =
capital.) Year after, same idea: You will keep bleeding money, because you =
borrowed short and loaned long and rates went up. But maybe something will =
change? Maybe rates will go back down. Maybe your borrowers will repay thei=
r bonds early and you=E2=80=99ll get to redeploy the money at higher rates.=
 Maybe your employees will find a new line of business to earn some fees. M=
aybe you=E2=80=99ll reverse the losses. Or not, maybe you=E2=80=99ll keep l=
osing $2.50 per year for five years and run out of capital and have to clos=
e the bank.=C2=A0But maybe my assumptions about your high deposit beta and =
long-term assets are unrealistically pessimistic: This is a simplistic exam=
ple, and at a real bank the result might be lower margins for a while, not =
constant losses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if instead of keeping their deposits =
at your bank and earning 3% interest, the depositors all asked for their mo=
ney back today? You would have to sell your bonds. You=E2=80=99d get about =
$87 for them. You would have a $13 loss=C2=A0<em>today</em>. All of the los=
ses that you=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>have taken over the next five years, =
from holding long-term bonds at low rates while deposit rates have gone up,=
 you will experience=C2=A0<em>now</em>. And you won=E2=80=99t have any time=
 to reverse them, because you have to sell the bonds now and give everyone =
their money back. Also you don=E2=80=99t have enough money: Selling the bon=
ds for $87 will raise $87, and you have $10 of capital, for a total of $97.=
 But your depositors want their $100 back, and you only have $97.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a bank that borrowed short to lend =
long, and rates go up, your portfolio of long-dated assets represents an=C2=
=A0<em>opportunity cost </em>over time:=C2=A0Instead of earning 5% on your =
loans, you=E2=80=99re stuck earning 2%. But if you have to sell those asset=
s, you turn that opportunity cost into a cash loss today. You pull the loss=
es forward in time and take them all now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now we have to talk about accounting. Oversimp=
lifying, there are two main ways for a bank to account for its assets:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The traditional way is to account for=
 them at cost, the price you paid for them. If you lend a customer $100, yo=
u have a $100 asset =E2=80=94=C2=A0the loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0on your balance =
sheet. (You deduct something for the possibility they won=E2=80=99t pay you=
 back,=C2=A0but let=E2=80=99s ignore that.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The other way is to account for them at their fair market value. =
If you buy a bond for $100, you can go look at the market price for that bo=
nd at the end of the quarter; if it=E2=80=99s $97.75, then you have a $97.7=
5 asset on your balance sheet. The other $2.25 is gone.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first approach gives you a reasonable pict=
ure of a bank that is continuing to operate as a bank: In my example, if yo=
u have $100 of bonds and $100 of deposits and the loans pay 2% and the depo=
sits cost 3% and you are losing $2.50 per year, your financial statements=
=C2=A0will=C2=A0<em>say that</em>. Your balance sheet=C2=A0will say that yo=
u have $100 of bonds, so you will ultimately have enough money to pay back =
your depositors, but your income statement will say you are losing money ea=
ch year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second approach gives you a reasonably acc=
urate picture of a bank that has to shut down today: In my example, your ba=
lance sheet will show that you have=C2=A0$87 of bonds at fair market value,=
 so you don=E2=80=99t have enough money to pay back all your depositors if =
you have to do it today.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally banks=E2=80=99 assets consisted =
mostly of=C2=A0<em>loans</em>, there was not much of a market for those loa=
ns, and the normal accounting approach was to account for them at cost. Mod=
ern banks=E2=80=99 assets include lots of=C2=A0<em>bonds</em>, there is a m=
arket for those bonds, and it is reasonably common to account for them at f=
air market value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Still, banks do=C2=A0<em>like </em>accounting for assets at cost,=
 and so they are allowed to=C2=A0designate bonds as =E2=80=9Cheld to maturi=
ty=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning that they have no plans to sell them =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and account for them at cost. (But then if they sell <em>any</e=
m> of their held-to-maturity bonds, they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30821211.285418/aHR0cHM6Ly92aWV3cG9pbnQucHdjLmNvbS9k=
dC91cy9lbi9wd2MvYWNjb3VudGluZ19ndWlkZXMvbG9hbnNfYW5kX2ludmVzdG1lbnQvbG9hbnN=
fYW5kX2ludmVzdG1lbnRfVVMvY2hhcHRlcl8zX2FjY291bnRpbmdfXzFfVVMvMzNfY2xhc3NpZm=
ljYXRpb25fb2ZfVVMuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB97215cbd" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> need t=
o reclassify=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of them as =E2=80=9Cavailable for sale=
=E2=80=9D</a> and account for them at fair market value, which could mean t=
aking a huge loss all at once.) In general it seems fair to say that the mo=
dern trend in financial-institution accounting is toward marking more thing=
s to market values, but there remain many exceptions.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From my simple example you can see why banks d=
on=E2=80=99t always like mark-to-market accounting. In my simple example, t=
he bank has $100 of deposits, $100 of bonds and $10 of capital. It is losin=
g money on interest rates, so its capital is going down, slowly. But it is =
solvent: It has assets of $110 ($100 of bonds plus $10 of cash) and liabili=
ties of only $100 (the deposits).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if the bank instead put out financial stat=
ements showing that it had $87 of bonds (their current market value), it wo=
uld be insolvent: It would have assets of $97 against liabilities of $100. =
And if its depositors read those financial statements, they=E2=80=99d say =
=E2=80=9Chey wait this bank is insolvent=E2=80=9D and rush to take their mo=
ney out. And then the bank=C2=A0<em>would have to sell those bonds for $87<=
/em>, and it really=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>be insolvent. The accounting c=
ould cause a run, which would require the assets to be sold at market value=
, which would result in taking all the losses today, which would result in =
actual insolvency.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One crude way that the actual US banking syste=
m deals with this problem is by letting banks account for their held-to-mat=
urity bonds at cost on their balance sheet, but then making them explain, s=
omewhere in the footnotes to the financial statements, their current market=
 value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> This feels like in some ways a fair compromise. On the other hand some=
one might read the footnotes! I mean, not most people. But someone might, a=
nd they might explain the footnotes in a readable way =E2=80=94=C2=A0they m=
