<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Do you think they <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30821211.285418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VtYWZvci5jb2=
0vYXJ0aWNsZS8wMy8xMS8yMDIzL2hlZGdlLWZ1bmRzLW9mZmVyLXRvLWJ1eS1kZXBvc2l0cy1zd=
HVjay1hdC1zaWxpY29uLXZhbGxleS1iYW5r/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf46fc685" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> got any trades in</a>?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge funds are offering to buy startups=E2=80=
=99 deposits stranded at Silicon Valley Bank for as little as 60 cents on t=
he dollar, pitching expensive but crucial lifelines to founders unable to a=
ccess their cash after the lender collapsed yesterday, people familiar with=
 the matter said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Firms better known for investing in distressed=
 debt, including Oaktree, one of the people said, are fanning out to startu=
ps in the wake of the bank=E2=80=99s failure and seizure by the Federal Ins=
urance Deposit Corp. on Friday. Its collapse left hundreds of startups =E2=
=80=94 as well as the venture funds that backed them =E2=80=94 unable to ac=
cess their cash to meet payroll and other expenses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bids range from 60 to 80 cents on the dollar, =
the people said, reflecting a range of expectations for how much of the uni=
nsured deposits =E2=80=94 those that exceed the FDIC=E2=80=99s $250,000-per=
-customer cap =E2=80=94 will ultimately be recovered once the bank=E2=80=99=
s assets are sold or wound down.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from Semafor on Saturday, and we now k=
now the answer is 100 cents on the dollar. When we talked about this on Fri=
day, I figured plausible answers ranged from 95 to 100, with 100 being the =
most likely outcome. If you are a startup who woke up today needing to=C2=
=A0make payroll, you might have been tempted by 60, even though it was obje=
ctively way too low. Except that when you woke up=C2=A0<em>today=C2=A0</em>=
the FDIC had already said you=E2=80=99d be able to get 100 cents on the dol=
lar immediately. Things were less certain on Saturday, but you probably did=
n=E2=80=99t need to make payroll on Saturday. Seems unlikely that Oaktree d=
id much business (or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
